The first installment of that payment $4.8 billion was wasted, propping up the currency long enough, in the words of one IMF official, ``to let the oligarchs get their money out of the country''.
Then Yeltsin reversed his commitments, let the ruble devalue anyway, began printing money with abandon and fired virtually every reformer in his government resulting in a collapse of the IMF agreements and the indefinite suspension of its aid program.
Now, inside the IMF and on Capitol Hill, there are recriminations over ``who lost Russia.''
